In vitro study was performed using CHO-K1 (normal cells) and HeLa and PC-3 (cancer cells). The cells were embedded by immersing the hydrogel into solution containing cells at designated times (12, 24, and 48 h). SEM images depicted cell-embedded dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel, revealing the attachment of different cell type (CHO-K1, HeLa, and PC-3) to the surface pores of the hydrogel (Fig. S12). Furthermore, the electrochemical performance of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel for real samples were analyzed against normal-simulated human serum and cancer-simulated human serum as given in Fig. S13. The sensor showed change in the resistance signal for cancer-simulated human serum at 39.6 kΩ in comparison to 65.8 kΩ for normal-simulated human serum sample [47,48]. In addition to this, the resistance of the sample was observed after treatment with cell media at 0 day and 3 days of cell growth following culture (Fig. S14a). The resistance of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel showed change for cancer cell media for 3 days owing to the lowering of the pH in cancer condition signifying the cleavage of the boronate ester bonds in the sensor. Moreover, the resistance of the sensor changed in the presence of intracellular ROS level of cancer cells obtained from lysis solution of cells. HeLa and PC-3 lysis solution treated dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel demonstrated low resistance of 18.7 and 19.2 kΩ (Fig. S14b) in comparison to 28.6 kΩ for CHO-K1 lysis solution and 31.4 kΩ for control (PBS pH 7.4) highlighting the effect of intracellular ROS on the cleavage of diselenide bonds in the sensor. The sourcemeter resistance of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel was analyzed in the presence of mixed solution of cell media after 3 days and cell lysis solution of normal and cancer cells (Fig. S14c). The sensor showed elevated resistance for control and CHO-K1 media with lysis solution in comparison to HeLa media with lysis solution and PC-3 media with lysis solution demonstrating correlated results as in the presence of simulated human serum. Finally, the sensor resistance was compared for the cell lysis solution which contained the intracellular ROS (Fig. S15a) with that of H2O2 at same concentration as the lysis solution. It can be seen from Fig. S15b that the sensor demonstrated similar values of resistance when compared between normal and cancer cell lysis solution with that of the H2O2 solution highlighting the ability of the sensor to distinguish samples based on cancer level progress rather than the type of cancer cells. Additionally, the initial resistance of the control hydrogel (0 h, media only) measured 29.1 kΩ, 30.6 kΩ, and 29.1 kΩ for CHO-K1, HeLa, and PC-3, respectively, as illustrated in Fig. 5
a. The resistance rose to 31.9 kΩ, 33.4 kΩ, and 35.7 kΩ for dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel-immersed in CHO-K1 for 12, 24, and 48 h, respectively. In contrast to the normal cell line, HeLa and PC-3 showed a decrease of resistance to 21.7 kΩ and 20.4 kΩ after 12 h treatment, which further declined to 14.6 kΩ and 14.9 kΩ after 48 h treatment. The sourcemeter resistance of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel was evaluated as a function of varying cellular concentration from 101–105 cells/mL. It was observed (Fig. S16) that the resistance of the sensor in presence of CHO-K1 cells varied from 13.3 to 14.8 kΩ in comparison to HeLa and PC-3 cells which showed a decrease in the sensor resistance from 11.4 to 7.82 kΩ (HeLa) and 12.2 to 7.93 kΩ (PC-3) respectively. Furthermore, the limit of detection (LOD) of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel was evaluated for detecting cancer cells via electrochemical pathway (Fig. S17). The LOD for HeLa was obtained as 14.9 cells/mL and for PC-3 as 13.7 cells/mL which in comparison to the detection limit of other published electrochemical sensors demonstrates the higher sensitivity of the dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel in detection of cancer cells ( Table S1
) [49–55]. Moreover, dsCD-PD(HA) Hydrogel was subjected to alternating current (AC), and the electrical impedance was assessed using EIS to elucidate the impact of cell treatment on electrical properties (Fig. S18). The impedance of CHO-K1-embedded hydrogel was observed at 3.82 kΩ (48 h), surpassing that of HeLa and PC-3 cells (0.88 kΩ and 1.21 kΩ, respectively). Additionally, the wireless analysis results (Fig. 5 b) mirrored an analogous pattern in the previous data, illustrating a lower signal for HeLa and PC-3 cells. The increase in resistance of normal cells was attributed to cell accumulation in the hydrogel, whereas in cancer cells, ROS played a role in increasing conductivity. Moreover, the wireless results demonstrate the successful distinction between normal and cancer cells on the basis of the differentiated intracellular ROS levels and the environmental pH which highlights its future potential as a noninvasive real-time monitoring device for cancer detection [56].
